the astounding efforts by Ukrainians to establish institutions of higher learning in the unique democratic spirit of Tomáš Garrigue Masaryk. The book also explores Ukrainian scholarly and professional societies, museum and archival collections, scholarly publishing, and little-known intellectual connections between Ukrainian émigré scholars and their colleagues in Czechoslovakia and various other European countries. Scholars in Exile brings to light an interesting facet of modern Ukrainian history, allowing for a better understanding of the general intellectual and institutional history of Ukraine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aUkrainiansxIntellectual lifezCzechoslovakia. 0aUkrainiansxSocial conditionszCzechoslovakia. 0aUkrainiansxSocial life and customszCzechoslovakia. 0aUkrainianszCzechoslovakiaxIntellectual life. 0aUkrainianszCzechoslovakiaxSocial conditions. 0aUkrainianszCzechoslovakiaxSocial life and customs. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh  aCzechoslovakia.  aPrague.  aTomáš Garrigue Masaryk.  aUkraine.  aUkrainian history.  aUkrainians.  aexiles.  ahigher education in Ukraine.  ainstitutional history.  aintellectual life.  apolitical refugees.  ascholarly publishing.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781487538705zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487538705zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487538705/original  a978-3-11-069045-3 University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA